    {
      "id": "4e91b666_dad62e52",
      "file_path": "docs/sections/services/pm-subscription-handler/configuration.rst",
      "patchset_number": 1,
      "line": 101,
      "message": "Maybe you should specify that these \"xNF names\" contained within the list are actually regexes.\n\nI don't think you have explicitly stated anywhere that the application is written in python, it might be worth doing so as there are some differences in the methods available between python and java for example.\n\nJava offers a method called matches which matches the entire string to the regex, python doesn't have that and to get the same result you need to change your regex, so you should probably indicate that the regex will be interpreted by python and which method (search, match, findall, finditer) will be used and how it will be used.\nI realise that may seem a bit extreme, but when you are designing a regex for something the more information you have about the environment the less likely you are to run into weird issues where it works locally but not in production.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 4023,
        "name": "Joseph O'Leary",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "joseph.o.leary@est.tech",
        "username": "JoeOLeary"
      },
      "updated": "2019-12-02 10:27:49.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": null,
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "8c92bb88_a0ff4fe5",
      "file_path": "docs/sections/services/pm-subscription-handler/configuration.rst",
      "patchset_number": 1,
      "line": 137,
      "message": "It might be worth mentioning that this is a list of strings, and if a regex is included it is expected that the blueprint or network function itself is capable of expanding it.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 4023,
        "name": "Joseph O'Leary",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "joseph.o.leary@est.tech",
        "username": "JoeOLeary"
      },
      "updated": "2019-12-02 10:27:49.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": null,
      "unresolved": true
    },
